252
00:27:01.084 --> 00:27:04.444
to last year's enacted budget and does not reflect a cut in the NCI,

253
00:27:04.864 --> 00:27:07.344
despite the difficult fiscal environment we're in right now.

254
00:27:08.204 --> 00:27:11.924
I think this reflects a vote of confidence by the entire government in the

255
00:27:11.964 --> 00:27:15.264
mission and the execution of that mission by the National Cancer Institute.

256
00:27:18.144 --> 00:27:20.924
We haven't changed our commitment to funding, but what has changed is how we

257
00:27:20.964 --> 00:27:23.924
deliver that funding, but maybe not as much as you might think.

258
00:27:26.184 --> 00:27:29.504
The NIH has adopted a new unified funding strategy.

259
00:27:29.664 --> 00:27:33.244
At its core, this is about no longer using a strict pay line, a

260
00:27:33.264 --> 00:27:36.404
numerical cutoff that determines what grants get funded.

261
00:27:37.364 --> 00:27:41.064
We are now also considering additional factors like alignment with the

262
00:27:41.144 --> 00:27:44.824
NIH mission, balance across our scientific portfolio,

263
00:27:45.424 --> 00:27:48.924
and career stage, especially supporting early-stage investigators.

264
00:27:49.524 --> 00:27:52.384
But let me be extremely clear about this.

265
00:27:52.944 --> 00:27:56.644
Peer review and scientific merit remain the most

266
00:27:56.684 --> 00:28:00.323
important factors in determining whether a grant is funded or not.

267
00:28:00.844 --> 00:28:03.744
There simply is no longer a line in the sand like there used to be.

268
00:28:04.964 --> 00:28:08.144
Now we use what we call Select Pay, and it's not brand new.

269
00:28:08.204 --> 00:28:11.804
We always used to use Select Pay for about 15% of our portfolio,

270
00:28:12.584 --> 00:28:14.484
but now we're using it in all our funding decisions.

271
00:28:14.764 --> 00:28:18.664
Decisions are still driven by science, and the goal is to complement peer review

272
00:28:18.744 --> 00:28:22.304
so that we can move and make more strategic decisions about how we invest now.

273
00:28:23.564 --> 00:28:27.424
I've also heard concern about transparency and politicization, and I

274
00:28:27.464 --> 00:28:29.264
want to address that directly.

275
00:28:30.224 --> 00:28:33.684
Funding decisions at the NCI are driven by scientific expertise,

276
00:28:34.284 --> 00:28:37.244
peer review, and our core mission to reduce the burden of cancer.

277
00:28:38.604 --> 00:28:42.344
As director, I am part of that process, but these decisions are

278
00:28:42.413 --> 00:28:46.314
grounded in science and informed by the judgment of experienced researchers and

279
00:28:46.383 --> 00:28:47.284
program leadership.

280
00:28:48.204 --> 00:28:51.904
I am the political appointee with final say over all NCI

281
00:28:51.944 --> 00:28:55.844
grants, and that is consistent with how NCI has operated since the

282
00:28:55.884 --> 00:28:59.034
passage of the National Cancer Act in 1971.

283
00:29:02.844 --> 00:29:06.744
The second aspect of our funding approach is how we are using multi-year or upfront

284
00:29:06.784 --> 00:29:10.634
funding. I know there's some uncertainty around this, so let me clarify how

285
00:29:10.684 --> 00:29:14.484
it works. Foremost, we are maintaining a similar proportion of

286
00:29:14.524 --> 00:29:16.754
multi-year funding as in the prior year.

287
00:29:17.833 --> 00:29:20.984
A helpful way to think about multi-year funding is a simple analogy.

288
00:29:21.024 --> 00:29:24.104
It's like the difference between financing a car and buying it outright.

289
00:29:24.534 --> 00:29:27.684
Traditionally, we funded grants like financing a car.

290
00:29:27.724 --> 00:29:31.584
We pay them one year at a time. With multi-year funding, for some grants, we

291
00:29:31.624 --> 00:29:34.504
provide the full amount upfront, more like buying the car in cash.

292
00:29:35.224 --> 00:29:38.794
An advantage we realize is then we are no longer on the hook for the out years,

293
00:29:38.864 --> 00:29:41.204
years, say, two, three, four, and five in a five-year grant.

294
00:29:42.764 --> 00:29:46.504
But I do not see enthusiasm in Congress for a continuing increase in

295
00:29:46.544 --> 00:29:48.724
multi-year funding, and they do have a say in this.

296
00:29:49.324 --> 00:29:52.424
Rest assured, though, no matter what the multi-year funding decisions are, we have

297
00:29:52.484 --> 00:29:54.584
plans to execute the mission of the NCI.

298
00:30:01.284 --> 00:30:04.924
Now, that changes how things look in terms of new award counts, but it doesn't

299
00:30:04.964 --> 00:30:07.504
change how much research we're actually supporting.

300
00:30:07.864 --> 00:30:11.564
I think a concept that might be helpful is to think in terms of science years.

301
00:30:12.264 --> 00:30:15.934
When we fund a grant year by year, we're investing in one science year at a

302
00:30:16.024 --> 00:30:19.664
time. When we fund a grant up front, we're investing in several years of science

303
00:30:19.744 --> 00:30:23.424
all at once. And I want to emphasize, this is a managed approach, not a

304
00:30:23.464 --> 00:30:24.304
wholesale shift.

305
00:30:25.164 --> 00:30:28.994
Guidance from Congress for fiscal year 2026 is to maintain multi-year

306
00:30:29.084 --> 00:30:31.904
funding at roughly the same proportion as fiscal year

307
00:30:31.914 --> 00:30:35.908
'25.At the same time, NCI continues to support the

308
00:30:35.968 --> 00:30:39.128
extramural community at a level of 5.5 billion a year.

309
00:30:39.148 --> 00:30:43.108
The multi-year funding reflects about $480 million of that.

310
00:30:43.698 --> 00:30:45.428
There are also important downstream effects.

311
00:30:45.768 --> 00:30:49.498
We get more flexibility to support new ideas, and it provides greater

312
00:30:49.568 --> 00:30:53.388
stability and continuity for investigators who are less exposed to the

313
00:30:53.448 --> 00:30:56.988
uncertainties of annual continuing and resolutions and other disruptions.

314
00:31:00.448 --> 00:31:03.827
Related to multi-year funding, we are also thinking about new ways to support

315
00:31:03.898 --> 00:31:05.508
high-risk, high-reward science.

316
00:31:06.268 --> 00:31:09.868
One concept we're exploring is funding the first two years of a five-year project,

317
00:31:10.428 --> 00:31:14.308
and then after an administrative review, deciding to continue based on what

318
00:31:14.368 --> 00:31:18.308
we learn. This lets us support ideas that might not have been

319
00:31:18.368 --> 00:31:20.268
funded under a traditional five-year model.

320
00:31:20.948 --> 00:31:23.908
I think that many of us who've been on study sections have experienced or

321
00:31:23.948 --> 00:31:27.618
encountered grants that look pretty good, have clever, innovative ideas,

322
00:31:28.128 --> 00:31:31.628
but say, specific aim one might look a little risky, and it doesn't get a good

323
00:31:31.668 --> 00:31:35.428
score on that basis. Those are the type of grants we want to, in some ways,

324
00:31:35.588 --> 00:31:39.068
rescue so that we will fund the first two years and see if

325
00:31:39.128 --> 00:31:42.808
specific aim two works out, and if it does, we can make a very rapid

326
00:31:42.828 --> 00:31:45.088
administrative decision to fully fund that.

327
00:31:46.808 --> 00:31:49.998
Another change you're seeing is how we communicate scientific priorities.

328
00:31:50.388 --> 00:31:54.008
We're placing much more emphasis on NIH and NCI highlighted topics

329
00:31:54.288 --> 00:31:57.908
and less on traditional NOFOs, Notices of Funding Opportunities.

330
00:31:59.608 --> 00:32:03.108
Highlighted topics allow us to signal areas of opportunity without

331
00:32:03.148 --> 00:32:06.688
constraining innovation. Instead of shaping your research to fit a

332
00:32:06.768 --> 00:32:10.528
specific call, you can pursue ideas and align them

333
00:32:11.268 --> 00:32:14.168
where you see the opportunity. We want to encourage

334
00:32:14.208 --> 00:32:17.688
investigator-initiated science while still providing some guidance.

335
00:32:20.668 --> 00:32:24.578
I also realize that there is some concern about the stance of the NCI and the

336
00:32:24.578 --> 00:32:26.608
NIH on performing research on animals.

337
00:32:27.168 --> 00:32:31.128
I would like to make clear that neither NIH nor NCI are

338
00:32:31.188 --> 00:32:32.528
forbidding animal research.

339
00:32:33.528 --> 00:32:37.408
When I reflect on my own career, I can say that the progress of my own laboratory

340
00:32:37.468 --> 00:32:41.308
was greatly assisted at times by animal studies, and I understand that they can

341
00:32:41.348 --> 00:32:45.308
be very valuable. At the same time, I think that for

342
00:32:45.368 --> 00:32:48.988
ethical and for scientific reasons, it's essential that when we

343
00:32:49.008 --> 00:32:52.228
perform animal studies, we're able to describe why these experiments are

344
00:32:52.308 --> 00:32:54.848
necessary for the questions we want to answer.

345
00:32:55.818 --> 00:32:58.998
In practical terms, NCI would like to see an explicit

346
00:32:59.128 --> 00:33:02.348
justification for the necessity of animal studies when it's

347
00:33:02.368 --> 00:33:05.628
proposed. This doesn't have to be long, a few sentences will do.

348
00:33:06.508 --> 00:33:09.348
I would also strongly encourage you to include such a

349
00:33:09.408 --> 00:33:13.288
justification like this even in the abstract, because

350
00:33:13.348 --> 00:33:16.748
that is a part of the grant that's viewed by many people, including me.

351
00:33:18.208 --> 00:33:22.118
However, I also think it's important that this is not just a workaround.

352
00:33:22.128 --> 00:33:25.448
There is a changing current here associated with the new approach

353
00:33:25.488 --> 00:33:27.328
methodologies or NAM program.

354
00:33:28.648 --> 00:33:32.628
There's going to be more emphasis at NIH and the NCI to prioritize research

355
00:33:33.048 --> 00:33:35.848
that is more directly relevant to human biology.

356
00:33:35.868 --> 00:33:39.018
I think many of us who've worked with mice find them useful tools, but there are

357
00:33:39.048 --> 00:33:42.288
limitations to how relevant they always are to the human condition.

358
00:33:43.008 --> 00:33:46.648
The good news, though, is that advances in biological technology have made it

359
00:33:46.708 --> 00:33:49.888
easier than ever to answer complex questions using human tissues.

360
00:33:50.668 --> 00:33:53.538
I'm not sure the entire cancer community is even aware of these

361
00:33:53.568 --> 00:33:57.388
advances. However, I urge you to remember that as scientists,

362
00:33:57.448 --> 00:34:01.218
our job is to answer questions, and if human tissues can answer these

363
00:34:01.248 --> 00:34:05.188
questions with greater reliability than animal tissues, we should try

364
00:34:05.288 --> 00:34:08.348
very hard to include human tissues in our planning.

365
00:34:10.328 --> 00:34:13.669
So when you step back, the broader picture, I hope, should be reassuring,

366
00:34:14.248 --> 00:34:15.968
and if you agree, please spread the word.

367
00:34:16.788 --> 00:34:20.768
NCI's mission is steady, our commitment to the research enterprise

368
00:34:20.808 --> 00:34:24.708
is steady, and our focus remains on advancing the best science

369
00:34:24.908 --> 00:34:25.948
on behalf of patients.

370
00:34:27.609 --> 00:34:31.348
Our goal is to move forward in a way that gives investigators, institutions, and

371
00:34:31.448 --> 00:34:35.248
staff confidence that NCI will no longer-- Sorry.

372
00:34:35.649 --> 00:34:39.149
NCI will continue to support high-quality science with

373
00:34:39.188 --> 00:34:40.468
consistency and purpose.

374
00:34:42.388 --> 00:34:44.688
See, this is my first time around. Next time, I'll get that right.

375
00:34:46.808 --> 00:34:49.968
If you're doing research, if you're participating in a trial, if you're helping

376
00:34:50.008 --> 00:34:52.928
deliver a therapy, you're advocating for patients, you're part of

377
00:34:53.748 --> 00:34:56.087
our community, you are part of the NCI.

378
00:34:56.649 --> 00:34:58.928
This brings me to a question for all of you.

379
00:34:58.988 --> 00:35:02.468
What will you, as part of this community, do to bring the breakthroughs of the next

380
00:35:02.508 --> 00:35:06.288
quarter century? Where can you focus your efforts to make the cancer research

381
00:35:06.298 --> 00:35:09.588
system stronger, faster, and more effective for people with cancer?

382
00:35:10.528 --> 00:35:13.608
Let me challenge you to consider a few areas I believe are particularly important.

383
00:35:15.568 --> 00:35:19.148
First, competitiveness. The United States is no longer the

384
00:35:19.188 --> 00:35:21.768
world's only engine of biomedical innovation.

385
00:35:21.828 --> 00:35:25.578
Other countries like China, Australia, New Zealand, and some in Europe, are

386
00:35:25.588 --> 00:35:29.548
investing heavily and moving faster, particularly in early-stage clinical

387
00:35:29.588 --> 00:35:32.228
trials. I am not the only one noticing this.

388
00:35:33.068 --> 00:35:36.968
Other divisions at HHS have also been looking at this, and I expect NCI will help

389
00:35:36.988 --> 00:35:38.888
with boosting early-phase trial efficiency.

390
00:35:39.608 --> 00:35:43.508
We all know it takes too long in this country to move from a promising idea

391
00:35:43.588 --> 00:35:47.448
to testing it in humans. Some barriers are, of course, necessary

392
00:35:47.848 --> 00:35:51.448
to ensure safety and rigor. Others are simply inefficiencies that have

393
00:35:51.508 --> 00:35:52.868
accumulated over time.

394
00:35:53.828 --> 00:35:57.688
Fixing these will require coordination across biotech and pharma, the

395
00:35:57.768 --> 00:36:01.508
FDA and regulatory bodies, cancer centers, practitioners, patient

396
00:36:01.608 --> 00:36:05.568
advocates, and the NCI. I'm encouraged to see that all

397
00:36:05.608 --> 00:36:09.288
of these parties that I've spoken to are supportive of making trials faster,

398
00:36:09.768 --> 00:36:11.308
less expensive, and more efficient.

399
00:36:12.468 --> 00:36:15.998
Many of you will be hearing from me and others at the NCI over the next year

400
00:36:16.428 --> 00:36:19.908
in an effort to improve the speed and efficiency of the US clinical trial

401
00:36:20.028 --> 00:36:23.808
apparatus. I urge you to embrace the opportunity for change in a

402
00:36:23.868 --> 00:36:27.638
way that will benefit patients, clinical trialists, and the

403
00:36:27.668 --> 00:36:30.288
entire biomedical ecosystem of the United States.

404
00:36:33.148 --> 00:36:36.308
Another priority at the NCI that we continue to

405
00:36:36.328 --> 00:36:39.612
embraceIs training the next generation of researchers.

406
00:36:40.252 --> 00:36:44.132
I think about this not only as director of the NCI, but also

407
00:36:44.212 --> 00:36:46.552
as the proud parent of an early-stage investigator.

408
00:36:47.432 --> 00:36:50.592
I know they feel uncertain about this environment they're stepping into.

409
00:36:51.912 --> 00:36:54.712
Institutions are also responding to broader uncertainty.

410
00:36:56.032 --> 00:36:59.912
We see hiring delays, smaller startup packages, amid tighter

411
00:36:59.992 --> 00:37:03.852
resource allocation. And in that environment, early investigators who have

412
00:37:03.932 --> 00:37:07.252
smaller labs and shorter track records are often the most vulnerable.

413
00:37:07.892 --> 00:37:11.312
I understand why that creates anxiety, and I want to take that

414
00:37:11.352 --> 00:37:11.892
seriously.

415
00:37:12.752 --> 00:37:16.612
I want to assure you that NCI is still committed to supporting ESIs

416
00:37:16.972 --> 00:37:18.872
through our numerous training opportunities.

417
00:37:19.492 --> 00:37:22.852
If we want the next breakthrough, we must invest in the people who will discover

418
00:37:22.912 --> 00:37:26.852
it, and those are often early stage investigators pursuing bold,

419
00:37:27.312 --> 00:37:28.272
new ideas.

420
00:37:29.072 --> 00:37:32.432
I know the number of ESI R01s decreased in fiscal year

421
00:37:32.552 --> 00:37:36.352
2025. However, NCI is planning and budgeting this year to

422
00:37:36.392 --> 00:37:39.972
make more ESI awards in fiscal year '26 and return to the

423
00:37:40.012 --> 00:37:42.992
levels that we were used to all throughout the 2020s.

424
00:37:44.032 --> 00:37:47.792
Our support for ESIs comes in the form of structured pathways to independence

425
00:37:48.172 --> 00:37:50.772
and extended support beyond an initial grant period.

426
00:37:51.292 --> 00:37:54.512
Career stage is also considered in funding decisions to ensure

427
00:37:54.572 --> 00:37:58.432
ESIs are not crowded out by more established applicants.

428
00:38:00.192 --> 00:38:04.112
Among our many programs, we're also advancing a trans-NCI effort to help us

429
00:38:04.152 --> 00:38:07.922
take a fresh look at how we train the next generation based on the real needs of

430
00:38:07.922 --> 00:38:08.482
the community.

431
00:38:09.822 --> 00:38:13.732
This system only works if new investigators are given the opportunity to lead

432
00:38:14.172 --> 00:38:17.752
and if they believe this is a system worth committing their careers to.

433
00:38:17.892 --> 00:38:21.712
If you are an early stage investigator, I urge you to

434
00:38:21.732 --> 00:38:25.432
stay strong in your commitment. Despite the travails of the past year,

435
00:38:25.752 --> 00:38:29.192
the overall NCI funding picture is strong and young cancer

436
00:38:29.232 --> 00:38:33.192
researchers, and I think we often forget this, have never started

437
00:38:33.232 --> 00:38:37.132
their careers with more powerful tools or more knowledge at their

438
00:38:37.152 --> 00:38:39.092
disposal than there is today.

439
00:38:41.792 --> 00:38:45.652
Another area I want to highlight, close to my heart, is functional

440
00:38:45.732 --> 00:38:49.272
precision medicine. The idea is actually pretty simple.

441
00:38:49.852 --> 00:38:53.652
If you want to know whether a drug will work on a patient's tumor,

442
00:38:54.232 --> 00:38:58.192
take that living tumor tissue, expose it to the drug, and observe

443
00:38:58.232 --> 00:38:58.832
what happens.

444
00:38:59.912 --> 00:39:03.272
Instead of inferring whether a treatment will work based on genomics or model

445
00:39:03.372 --> 00:39:07.292
systems, functional precision medicine lets us learn directly from the patient's

446
00:39:07.352 --> 00:39:09.652
own biology in real time.

447
00:39:10.532 --> 00:39:14.192
You can often test multiple drugs simultaneously and make informed choices about

448
00:39:14.212 --> 00:39:18.132
what is most likely to work. This aligns with the broader NIH policy

449
00:39:18.172 --> 00:39:20.912
to increase use of direct human-based systems.

450
00:39:21.692 --> 00:39:25.432
To help move this forward, we've begun convening the community, first through a

451
00:39:25.492 --> 00:39:27.072
workshop at the beginning of July.

452
00:39:27.912 --> 00:39:29.392
Keep your eyes posted if you're interested.

453
00:39:30.092 --> 00:39:33.961
Keep your eyes peeled for the posting, that is, to define how NCI can

454
00:39:33.992 --> 00:39:37.792
support both intramural and extramural efforts in this space.

455
00:39:38.712 --> 00:39:42.012
Functional precision medicine has numerous applications for

456
00:39:42.032 --> 00:39:45.382
discovery, understanding biological

457
00:39:45.472 --> 00:39:49.132
vulnerabilities we've previously not identified, as a companion

458
00:39:49.172 --> 00:39:52.852
biomarker, and also as a tool for personalized treatment decisions,

459
00:39:53.252 --> 00:39:55.392
especially for people who have run out of options.

460
00:39:56.512 --> 00:40:00.492
I am confident this technology is more advanced and more feasible than

461
00:40:00.552 --> 00:40:03.452
most people in the cancer research community realize.

462
00:40:04.272 --> 00:40:07.672
I challenge you to think about how your work touches functional precision medicine.

463
00:40:08.232 --> 00:40:12.202
What are ways that you can answer questions important to your research using

464
00:40:12.232 --> 00:40:13.662
these exciting new technologies?

465
00:40:16.672 --> 00:40:20.532
And finally, I want to come back to something fundamental, population

466
00:40:20.592 --> 00:40:22.322
science, prevention, and access.

467
00:40:23.032 --> 00:40:26.512
We've made enormous progress in reducing cancer mortality, and a

468
00:40:26.552 --> 00:40:30.252
significant portion of that progress has come from prevention, especially

469
00:40:30.272 --> 00:40:33.792
reducing tobacco use, as well as from early detection.

470
00:40:34.652 --> 00:40:36.992
But those benefits are not reaching everyone equally.

471
00:40:37.692 --> 00:40:41.452
There are still communities where access to screening and prevention programs is

472
00:40:41.492 --> 00:40:41.912
limited.

473
00:40:42.872 --> 00:40:46.562
That's why we are introducing an effort called the Prevention, Screening, and Early

474
00:40:46.632 --> 00:40:49.852
Detection Initiative with the secretary's blessing

475
00:40:50.692 --> 00:40:53.592
to bring evidence-based screening to the underserved parts of the country.

476
00:40:54.371 --> 00:40:57.991
We'll start with counties in five states, and if it's successful, our vision is to

477
00:40:58.032 --> 00:41:01.472
expand what we learn to enhance screening access and care

478
00:41:01.572 --> 00:41:02.592
across the country.

479
00:41:03.432 --> 00:41:07.352
We are currently convening coordination meetings with operational divisions across

480
00:41:07.412 --> 00:41:11.092
the Department of Health and Human Services, and their contributions are going to

481
00:41:11.132 --> 00:41:15.022
be absolutely essential to realizing this initiative and

482
00:41:15.072 --> 00:41:15.732
implementing it.

483
00:41:16.832 --> 00:41:20.132
My message to you is to think about who you're not seeing in your work.

484
00:41:20.632 --> 00:41:22.632
Who is not participating in this trial?

485
00:41:23.222 --> 00:41:25.572
Who is not showing up for their screening appointments?

486
00:41:26.212 --> 00:41:29.632
Consider ways you can reach out to those people, because a breakthrough only

487
00:41:29.652 --> 00:41:31.552
