I think I'll ask close to my last question, as we are going

1208
01:22:07.181 --> 01:22:07.972
down on the clock.

1209
01:22:09.652 --> 01:22:13.052
I think there has been a decrease in trust in science.

1210
01:22:13.152 --> 01:22:14.712
I think there is no doubt about that.

1211
01:22:14.832 --> 01:22:18.232
How, as scientists, we can help the NCI to reverse that

1212
01:22:18.552 --> 01:22:19.232
distrust?

1213
01:22:21.892 --> 01:22:25.542
I think that's a great point. I think that is something the NCI can do, because I

1214
01:22:25.572 --> 01:22:29.252
think we are in a unique position of public trust that maybe isn't

1215
01:22:29.312 --> 01:22:33.122
shared by other institutes or other organs of

1216
01:22:33.152 --> 01:22:35.592
government. The way I

1217
01:22:36.692 --> 01:22:40.592
plan to do it is, for starters, I think we need to be, as a public health

1218
01:22:40.632 --> 01:22:44.352
community, I think we need to be universally more respectful.

1219
01:22:45.252 --> 01:22:48.672
If someone brings up an idea about a drug, about an

1220
01:22:48.732 --> 01:22:52.012
antihelminth, that they have read or

1221
01:22:52.072 --> 01:22:53.812
heard cures cancer,

1222
01:22:54.682 --> 01:22:58.582
the answer shouldn't be, "You ignorant rube, how hilarious that

1223
01:22:58.592 --> 01:23:02.412
you think this is the case." Instead, we, as scientists, should be

1224
01:23:02.432 --> 01:23:06.232
prepared to calmly lay out the data

1225
01:23:06.552 --> 01:23:10.452
that might support or refute the idea that this particular drug

1226
01:23:10.552 --> 01:23:14.532
that we might consider absurd does or does not contribute to

1227
01:23:14.572 --> 01:23:18.132
the treatment of cancer. If we can't do that, we're not doing our job,

1228
01:23:18.492 --> 01:23:21.832
and we're missing an opportunity to connect as a member of the

1229
01:23:21.872 --> 01:23:24.252
public that probably needs it the most.

1230
01:23:24.792 --> 01:23:28.612
So I think a lot of this really starts with just mutual respect, and

1231
01:23:28.651 --> 01:23:32.572
understand that when people are coming to you with funny ideas, they're

1232
01:23:32.672 --> 01:23:36.312
often desperate people that are suffering greatly because of their own

1233
01:23:36.372 --> 01:23:37.752
personal or

1234
01:23:38.932 --> 01:23:41.231
medical problems or medical problems of a loved one.

1235
01:23:43.512 --> 01:23:46.692
Well, I think I'll give you the chair's prerogative of having asked the last

1236
01:23:46.732 --> 01:23:47.112
question.

1237
01:23:49.112 --> 01:23:52.642
Well, I want to thank Dr. Lotai for being with us, and thank you for all the

1238
01:23:52.712 --> 01:23:54.172
questions that you have submitted.

1239
01:23:54.302 --> 01:23:54.302
Yeah.

1240
01:23:54.352 --> 01:23:58.032
And, I think this has been very helpful for understand some of the

1241
01:23:58.112 --> 01:24:01.912
questions we have in our mind, and thank you for providing this address to

1242
01:24:01.992 --> 01:24:03.912
us during the annual meeting. Thank you.

1243
01:24:04.252 --> 01:24:05.912
And I also just want to thank the ACR.

1244
01:24:06.312 --> 01:24:10.212
It's been a very valuable opportunity for me at this whole meeting

1245
01:24:10.292 --> 01:24:13.992
to engage with the cancer community in a way I haven't been able to do so far as

1246
01:24:14.372 --> 01:24:17.292
director, and it's been very valued to me, and I want to thank the ACR for that.

1247
01:24:17.642 --> 01:24:17.892
Great. Thank you.

1248
01:24:17.932 --> 01:24:18.572
Thank you so much.
